Workhub SaaS Backend - Design Note (Phase 1)

1) Architecture Overview
- Clean layered architecture separating Controller, Service, Repository, Security, and DTO layers.
- Stateless API secured via JWT; tenant identity extracted from JWT to enforce isolation.
- Simplicity first: a single PostgreSQL database, shared schema; horizontal scale via stateless app instances.

2) Layered Design
- Controller: I/O boundary, validation, mapping to service calls. No domain logic.
- Service: Orchestrates use cases, enforces tenant boundaries and authorization, defines transaction scopes with @Transactional.
- Repository: Spring Data JPA for persistence.
- Security: JwtAuthenticationFilter populates SecurityContext; TenantFilter derives tenant and sets TenantContext for downstream.
- DTOs: Request/Response models with validation to keep controllers/services strongly typed and stable.

3) Tenant Isolation
- Every entity extends a base model carrying tenantId (or explicitly includes tenantId).
- Tenant is resolved from JWT claims; the header Authorization: Bearer <token> is the single source of truth.
- Services validate tenant equality for read/write. Repositories include per-tenant finders where necessary.
- Result: no cross-tenant reads or writes, even if IDs are guessed.

4) Transaction Boundary
- Business transactions live in the Service layer annotated with @Transactional.
- Example: create project, then multiple tasks, then intentionally throw an exception.
- Because this is a single transaction, the exception triggers a rollback: neither the project nor the tasks remain persisted.
- Rationale: All-or-nothing semantics across aggregate boundaries ensure consistency.

5) Enterprise-Grade Considerations
- Stateless auth + short-lived JWTs enable horizontal scaling.
- Tenant isolation via data column + runtime validation is simple and efficient for many tenants per database.
- Clear boundaries + DTO validation reduce coupling and boost maintainability.
- Observability: correlation IDs enable request tracing and troubleshooting.
- Extensibility: can evolve to schema-per-tenant or database-per-tenant when requirements warrant it.

6) Future Enhancements
- Add migration tooling and database versioning (Flyway).
- Add audit logging and outbox pattern for reliable events.
- Introduce rate limiting and fine-grained authorization policies per tenant.

